    "source_sections": {
      "references": "",
      "remarks": "Positive odd integers $m$ such that none of $2^km+1$ are prime are called Sierpinski numbers - see [1113] for more details.\n\nErd\\H{o}s and Graham also ask more generally about $p_1^{k_1}\\cdots p_r^{k_r}m+1$ for distinct primes $p_i$, or $q_1\\cdots q_rm+1$ where the $q_i$ are primes congruent to $1\\pmod{4}$. (Dogmachine has noted in the comments this latter question has the trivial answer $m=1$ - perhaps some condition such as $m$ even is meant.)"
    },
    "source_state": "open",
    "tags": [
      "primes",
      "covering systems"
    ]
  },
